Moreover, the UV–vis absorption spectra of AuNPs, AuNPs/G6 and AuNPs/G6/GQDsx were studied (Fig. 5
                        A-D). As shown in Fig. 5-a, clearly, there is a strong absorption at 540 nm, which is consistent with the surface plasmon resonance in AuNPs. As illustrated in Fig. 5-b, when the G6 capped AuNPs is formed, the band at 540 nm for AuNPs is red-shifted to 543 nm, in that the local refractive index around the particles is increased [25]. After the GQDsx (x = 1, 2, 3) are introduced, the SPR of AuNPs and the characteristic peaks of GQDsx in AuNPs/G6/GQDs (Fig. 5B-c, 5C-d and 5D-e) are obviously observed, indicating that the AuNPs/G6/GQDsx composites are fabricated successfully. Specifically, as shown in Fig. 5B-c, 5C-d and 5D-e, the SPR of AuNPs in AuNPs/G6/GQDs1, AuNPs/G6/GQDs2 and AuNPs/G6/GQDs3 are all obviously blue-shifted to 532 nm, 540 nm and 518 nm, respectively. Furthermore, compared to the UV peaks of bare GQDsx (Fig. 2B), the characteristic peaks of GQDsx in AuNPs/G6/GQDsx exhibit different shifts (Table 1
                        ). Results indicate that the differences in the surface oxidation degree of GQDsx result in the different bonding strength between GQDsx and AuNPs/G6. Thus, the above results further confirm that the AuNPs/G6/GQDsx composites are constructed successfully, and also the changes of the surface oxidation degree of GQDs could be used to modulate the interaction of AuNPs and GQDs.
